{"title_page": "United Republican Party (Kenya)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox Political party\n|name          = United Republican Party\n|logo          = United Republican Party (Kenya) Logo.jpg\n|logo_size     = 150px\n|colorcode     = yellow\n|leader        = [[William Ruto]]\n|chairman      = \n|president     = \n|slogan        = ''Kusema na kutenda''\n|founder       = [[Charles Keter]]\n|foundation    = 15 January 2012\n|dissolved     = 8 September 2016\n|headquarters  = Nairobi  \n|ideology      = [[Liberalism]]              \n|national      = [[Jubilee Alliance]]\n|international = \n|website       = {{URL|www.urp.co.ke}}\n|country       = Kenya\n}}\n\nThe '''United Republican Party''' ('''URP''') was a political party in Kenya.\n\n==History==\nThe party was launched by [[William Ruto]], in conjunction with several Kenyan politicians allied to a faction of [[Orange Democratic Movement]] opposed to [[Raila Odinga]], as their vehicle for the [[Kenyan general election, 2013|March 2013 general elections]]. The party's launch was announced after a week of meetings on 15 January 2012.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201201160958.html Ruto, Allies Launch Political Party] Capital FM, 15 January 2012\n</ref> In December, William Ruto and the leaders of several other political parties, signed a pre-election coalition deal, in which Ruto became a running mate for [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] and URP received half the spoils of an election victory.<ref>[http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/?articleID=2000072150&story_title=Kenya-Raila,-Kalonzo-seal-deal-as-Mudavadi-joins-Uhuru,-Ruto Raila, Kalonzo seal deal as Mudavadi joins Uhuru, Ruto] Standard Media, 5 December 2012</ref> The party subsequently joined the [[Jubilee Alliance]], which nominated Kenyatta for the presidency. In the elections Kenyatta was elected president, whilst the URP emerged as the third-largest party in Parliament, winning 12 seats in the Senate and 76 in the National Assembly.\n\nIn 2016 the party pretended to merge into the [[Jubilee Party of Kenya|Jubilee Party]].<ref>[http://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/13-parties-wind-up-today-for--Jubilee-merger/1064-3373120-qu3trbz/index.html 13 parties wind up today for Jubilee merger] Daily Nation, 8 September 2016</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kenyan political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Political parties disestablished in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 disestablishments in Kenya]]\n\n\n{{Africa-party-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox Political party\n|name          = United Republican Party\n|logo          = United Republican Party (Kenya) Logo.jpg\n|logo_size     = 150px\n|colorcode     = yellow\n|leader        = [[William Ruto]]\n|chairman      = \n|president     = \n|slogan        = ''Kusema na kutenda''\n|founder       = [[Charles Keter]]\n|foundation    = 15 January 2012\n|dissolved     = 8 September 2016\n|headquarters  = Nairobi  \n|ideology      = [[Liberalism]]              \n|national      = [[Jubilee Alliance]]\n|international = \n|website       = {{URL|www.urp.co.ke}}\n|country       = Kenya\n}}\n\nThe '''United Republican Party''' ('''URP''') was a political party in Kenya.\n\n==History==\nThe party was launched by [[William Ruto]], in conjunction with several Kenyan politicians allied to a faction of [[Orange Democratic Movement]] opposed to [[Raila Odinga]], as their vehicle for the [[Kenyan general election, 2013|March 2013 general elections]]. The party's launch was announced after a week of meetings on 15 January 2012.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201201160958.html Ruto, Allies Launch Political Party] Capital FM, 15 January 2012\n</ref> In December, William Ruto and the leaders of several other political parties, signed a pre-election coalition deal, in which Ruto became a running mate for [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] and URP received half the spoils of an election victory.<ref>[http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/?articleID=2000072150&story_title=Kenya-Raila,-Kalonzo-seal-deal-as-Mudavadi-joins-Uhuru,-Ruto Raila, Kalonzo seal deal as Mudavadi joins Uhuru, Ruto] Standard Media, 5 December 2012</ref> The party subsequently joined the [[Jubilee Alliance]], which nominated Kenyatta for the presidency. In the elections Kenyatta was elected president, whilst the URP emerged as the third-largest party in Parliament, winning 12 seats in the Senate and 76 in the National Assembly.\n\nIn 2016 the party merged into the [[Jubilee Party of Kenya|Jubilee Party]].<ref>[http://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/13-parties-wind-up-today-for--Jubilee-merger/1064-3373120-qu3trbz/index.html 13 parties wind up today for Jubilee merger] Daily Nation, 8 September 2016</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kenyan political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Political parties disestablished in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 disestablishments in Kenya]]\n\n\n{{Africa-party-stub}}\n", "name_user": "154.123.168.129", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(R)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Republican_Party_(Kenya)"}
{"title_page": "George I, Duke of Pomerania", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=June 2011}}\n{{More footnotes|date=June 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox nobility\n| name = George I, Duke of Pomerania\n| image = Georg-i-pommern.jpg\n| caption = George I, Duke of Pomerania\n| noble family = [[House of Griffins]]\n| father = [[Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania]]\n| mother = [[Anna Jagiellon, Duchess of Pomerania|Anna of Poland]]\n| spouse = [[Amalie of the Palatinate]]<br/>[[Margarete of Brandenburg (1511\u20131577)|Margarete of Brandenburg]]\n| issue = [[Philip I, Duke of Pomerania]]\n| issue-link = #Marriages and issue\n| birth_date = {{birth_date|1493|4|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1531|5|10|1493|4|11|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Szczecin|Stettin]]\n}}\n'''George I of Pomerania''' ({{lang-de|Herzog Georg I. von Pommern}}; 11 April 1493 &ndash; 10 May 1531) was a Duke of [[Pomerania]] from the [[House of Griffins]].\n\n== Life ==\nGeorge was the eldest son of Duke [[Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania|Bogislaw X of Pomerania]] and his second wife [[Anna Jagiellon, Duchess of Pomerania|Anna of Poland]], a daughter of King [[Casimir IV Jagiello|Casimir IV]] of Poland.  He was named after his uncle and godfather, Duke [[Georg, Duke of Saxony|Georg the Bearded]] of Saxony, who had married the younger sister of George's mother.  As a child, George spent time at the court of his uncle and godfather in Saxony, which resulted in a lifetime friendship.\n\nGeorge essentially continued the policies of his father.  He worked energetically on limiting the power of the cities and the nobility. He pursued a policy of limiting the suzerainty of Brandenburg. In 1493 he concluded with Elector [[John Cicero, Elector of Brandenburg|John Cicero]] the [[Treaty of Pyritz]] by which Pomerania was to gain [[imperial immediacy]] within the Holy Roman Empire, of the same rank as Brandenburg, which again received the succession in Pomerania once the ducal house would become extinct in the male line. However, when - unlike as expected - the duke successfully procreated - John Cicero intrigued against Pomerania gaining imperial recognition as imperial estate. \n\nAfter he and his brother [[Barnim XI, Duke of Pomerania|Barnim IX]] took up government jointly, George showed an interest in the efforts of the [[Reformation]], yet he personally remained faithful to the Catholic church. George was introduced to government by his father at an early age.  In 1520 he was already active at the court of Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] and participated in the [[Diet of Worms]] in 1521 and the Diet of [[Nuremberg]] in 1523.\n\nWhen in 1524 a military conflict threatened with Brandenburg, George crafted an alliance with King [[Sigismund I of Poland]], which was directed against Brandenburg and Duke [[Albert of Prussia]] and against the followers of the Reformation.  Nevertheless, he failed to suppress the Reformation in his country; he could in the end only steer it onto moderate tracks.\n\nAfter the [[First Diet of Speyer|Diet of Speyer]] in 1526 he tried to approach Brandenburg. Due to Brandenburg claims and the refusal of the Pomeranian estates to cooperate, the negotiations took until 1529. In the meantime, Brandenburg once again threatened to resolve the conflict using its military. But on 26 August 1529, a compromise was struck, the [[Treaty of Grimnitz]], with Elector [[Joachim I, Elector of Brandenburg|Joachim I]] of Brandenburg thanks to the mediation of the Dukes [[Eric I, Duke of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Eric I]] of Brunswick-G\u00f6ttingen-Calenberg and [[Henry II, Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel|Henry the Younger]] of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel. George would marry Joachim's daughter [[Margaret of Brandenburg]] and Brandenburg would recognise Pomerania's imperial immediacy.\n\nDomestically, a dispute with his brother Barnim IX, who wanted to divide the country, began after the Treaty of Grimnitz had been ratified.  A large part of the Estates backed Barnim because they feared that once George had resolved the dispute with Brandenburg, he would turn his efforts against the reformation, and also because they were hoping that Barnim might be easier to influence than George.  The situation changed somewhat after George died, aged 38, at [[Szczecin|Stettin]], as his son and successor [[Philip I, Duke of Pomerania|Philip I]], joined the Reformation.  Nevertheless, the country was split into Pomerania-Wolgast (ruled by Philip I) and Pomerania-Szczecin (ruled by Barnim IX).\n\n== Marriages and issue ==\nGeorge I was married twice. In his first marriage, he married [[Amalie of the Palatinate|Amalie]] (1490\u20131524), daughter of Elector Palatine [[Philip, Elector Palatine|Philip]] and Margaret of Bavaria.  They had the following children:\n* Bogislaw XI (1514-1514)\n* [[Philip I, Duke of Pomerania|Philip I]] (1515\u20131560) married to Maria of Saxony\n* Margaret (1518\u20131569), married Duke [[Ernest III, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen|Ernest III]] of Brunswick-Grubenhagen\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Cranach the Younger Portrait of Philip I of Pomerania.jpg|Portrait of Philip I of Pomerania by Lucas Cranach the Younger\nFile:Margaretha of Saxony.jpg|Maria of Saxony, by Lucas Cranach the Elder\nFile:Ernest III de Brunswick-Grubenhagen 04110.JPG|Ernest III, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen by Cranach\nFile:Cranach the Elder Margaret of Pomerania.jpg|Princess Margaret of Pomerania-Wolgast (1518\u20131569) by Lucas Cranach the Elder\n</gallery>\n\nHis second wife was [[Margarete of Brandenburg (1511\u20131577)|Margarete of Brandenburg]] (1511\u20131577), daughter of Elector [[Joachim I, Elector of Brandenburg|Joachim]] of Brandenburg and [[Elizabeth of Denmark, Electress of Brandenburg|Elizabeth of Denmark]].  They had one daughter:\n* Georgia (1531\u20131574), married Count Stanislaus Latalski of Labischin\n\n== Ancestors ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|align=center|collapsed=yes\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1 = '''George I, Duke of Pomerania''' (1493-1531)\n| 2 = [[Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania]] (1454-1523)\n| 3 = [[Anna Jagiellon, Duchess of Pomerania|Anna Jagiellonica]] (1476-1503)\n| 4 = [[Eric II, Duke of Pomerania|Eric II of Pomerania]] (1425-1474)\n| 5 = [[Sophie of Pomerania, Duchess of Pomerania|Sophia of Pomerania-Stolp]]\n| 6 = [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]] (1427-1492)\n| 7 = [[Elisabeth of Austria (1436\u20131505)]]\n| 8 = [[Wartislaw IX, Duke of Pomerania|Wartislaw IX of Pomerania-Wolgast]] (1400-1457)\n| 9 = Sophie of Saxe-Lauenburg-Ratzeburg\n| 10 = [[Bogislaw IX, Duke of Pomerania|Bogislaw IX of Pomerania-Stolp]] (1407-1446)\n| 11 = Maria of Mazovia\n| 12 = [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw II Jagie\u0142\u0142o]] (1348-1434)\n| 13 = [[Sophia of Halshany]] (1405-1461)\n| 14 = Emperor [[Albert II, Holy Roman Emperor|Albert II of Habsburg]] (1397-1439)\n| 15 = [[Elisabeth of Luxembourg]] (1409-1442)\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[House of Griffins]]\n\n== References and sources ==\n* {{NDB|6|223|224|Georg I. von Pommern-Wolgast|Roderich Schmidt}}\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcelang|de|Brautfahrt|Brautfahrt (L\u00fcbsche Sage)}}\n* [http://www.ruegenwalde.com/greifen/geo-1/geo-1.htm www.ruegenwalde.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110604212002/http://www.genealogie-mittelalter.de/pommern_herzoege_von/georg_1_herzog_von_pommern_+_1531.html genealogie-mittelalter.de]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Griffins]]|11 April|1493|9 or 10 May|1531}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Bogislaw X, Duke of Pomerania|Bogislaw X]]|rows=1}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of Pomeranian duchies and dukes|Dukes of Pomerania]]|years=1523\u20131531|regent2=with his brother [[Barnim IX, Duke of Pomerania|Barnim IX]]|years2=1523\u20131532|rows=1}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Barnim IX, Duke of Pomerania|Barnim IX]]|after2=[[Philip I, Duke of Pomerania|